6/21/25

* I wrote this while sitting by the fireplace on a camping trip in southern Vermont.

The light from the fire danced on every surface it touched,
like the inverted image of an action hero
on the wall behind an onlooking audience.

The scent of burnt caramel invaded my nostrils,
seductive and crude in the lingering air,
like a newborn spring poppy or a ripe musk melon,
elusive and intimate, like faded childhood memories.

The hot coals gently roared and crackled
like a thousand distant lions, embattled,
or like a muscle-car engine burst, sizzling out,
as distance traded volume for tranquility.

The fire's warm hand caressed my cheek,
calling me into its tender embrace,
and as I reached blindly into that bright hive,
with embers buzzing like jealous bees,
the warm Vermont night pierced my hand
and buried its venom deep into my flesh.